        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Wells Fargo executives are optimistic that the Federal Reserve will soon <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-04-02-2025-h2-3-lift-the-asset-cap" target="_blank">lift the asset cap</a> that has constrained the bank’s growth for seven years. The restriction has cost the bank an estimated $36 billion in profits. The optimism around the ban lift is high; however, the process requires a final vote by the Fed board.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The restriction was imposed on the bank after the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-04-02-2025-h2-4-2016-fake-accounts-scandal" target="_blank">2016 fake accounts scandal</a>. The bank’s staff opened millions of unauthorized customer accounts to meet aggressive sales targets. The Fed restricted the bank, capping its total assets at $1.95 trillion until it could demonstrate significant improvements in risk management, corporate governance, and internal controls.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
