        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-feb-4-2.jpg" alt="PLOT TWIST" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Baijiu is China’s most popular spirit and the world’s most valuable alcoholic category</strong>, with a $161 billion market value. It is made from sorghum or grains and has 35–60% ABV and various aroma types. Brands like Moutai and Wuliangye dominate, making them a cultural and business staple in China.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Whisky is valued at $72.7 billion</strong>, making it the second most valuable segment, led by Scotch and premium global brands.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span>Tequila, Vodka, and Brandy are in close competition, with brand values ranging from <strong>$5.5 billion to $7.3 billion</strong>, reflecting their growing global appeal.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>The aperitif market, valued at $1.97 billion</strong>, includes drinks like Campari, Aperol, and Vermouth, traditionally consumed before meals. Popular in Europe, especially Italy and France, it’s growing globally due to rising cocktail culture and demand for lower-alcohol, herbal, and bitter-flavored spirits.</p>
        </mj-text>
